				\begin{document}$${\rm{JM}}=\frac{\left|{\bf{jerk}}\right|}{\left|{\bf{velocity}}\right|}$$\end{document}JM=jerkvelocitywhere velocity and jerk were calculated as the first and third (approximate) derivatives, respectively, of the translation or rotation resultant vector. As in other control movement studies, the jerk magnitude was divided by the velocity magnitude (or speed) so that the metric of jerkiness was not confounded by changes in overall movement speed28,29.
